          "url": "https://www.azcentral.com/story/opinion/op-ed/2022/11/19/trump-should-run-2024-so-lose-primary-desantis-youngkin/10717708002/",
          "title": "Want to stop Trump once and for all? Let him run in 2024",
          "body": "Opinion: This was never going to end with Donald Trump stepping away on his own. Haven't you read stories?\n\nWe're still counting votes from the midterms, but the 2024 election has already begun.\n\nIn a low-energy speech on Tuesday night, Donald Trump announced his anticipated candidacy at Mar-a-Lago. The former president promised to \"make America great and glorious again,\" called \"rotten\" U.S. cities \"cesspools of blood\" and near the close, stated, \"I am a victim. I am a victim.\"\n\nNot exactly \"a shining city on a hill,\" but this is Trump we're talking about.\n\nHe previewed his campaign two weeks ago, firing at potential rivals during a Latrobe, Penn., campaign rally for Senate candidate Mehmet Oz and gubernatorial candidate Doug Mastriano. (Oz lost by 4.5%; Mastriano lost by 14.4%.)\n\nTrump read 2024 presidential polls just three days before the 2022 election. \"There it is, Trump at 71. Ron DeSanctimonious at 10 percent,\" Trump said. \"Mike Pence at 7; oh, Mike Pence [is] doing better than I thought.\"\n\nSeveral Republicans made fun of Trump's lame nickname for Florida's non-sanctimonious governor, while others were outraged - including those who supported The Donald in the past.\n\nA few days later, Trump took on Gov. Glenn Youngkin, R-Va., with an uglier attack.\n\n\"Young Kin (now that's an interesting take. Sounds Chinese, doesn't it?),\" Trump posted on his Truth Social network. Then he blasted Lt. Gov. Winsome Earle-Sears, R-Va., while taking full credit for the pair's 2021 victories.\n\nNeither DeSantis nor Youngkin responded in kind. What's the point? Like the scorpion told the frog, it is his nature. The ex-president's attacks revealed his own insecurity, more than anything.\n\nThe fear is understandable. DeSantis won reelection by nearly 20% and his state party crushed Democrats up and down the ticket. That's a far sight better than Trump's performance.\n\nKari Lake and Blake Masters lost in Arizona, the Pennsylvania ticket sunk hard, and would-be senators Don Bolduc and Adam Laxalt lost in New Hampshire and Nevada, respectively. Add in Trump's lousy picks for gubernatorial and House races, and you have an unparalleled disaster for the GOP.\n\nActually, not unparalleled if you consider his dismal record in 2018 and 2020. Trump might have eked out an electoral college win against the deeply unpopular Hillary Clinton in 2016, but it's been losses ever since.\n\nMany right-leaning politicos pleaded with the 76-year-old Trump to step aside for fresher leaders. That was never going to happen. And if he doesn't win the GOP nom, he's likely to mount a third-party run, helping Democrats once again.\n\nOf course, he should back off for the good of the party. But he's never cared about the good of the party. For all we know this candidacy is just another way to gather donations or avoid indictment.\n\nIn the long run, it's healthier for the GOP that Trump does run for president - and is soundly defeated in the primaries. If DeSantis, Pence or Youngkin seek the nomination, let them fight for it. The only way the party turns the page is for voters to do the turning.\n\nNo backroom deals between Bushes and McConnells will solve the Trump dilemma. The grassroots made him and the grassroots are the only ones who can retire him to the back nine at Mar-a-Lago.\n\nBesides, Trump stepping away of his own accord was never how this story was going to end. Haven't you read stories?\n\nGoing all the way back to first storytellers, it's not like the Titans stepped aside and gave Zeus the C-suite. The young upstarts had to defeat the old guard, fair and square. If any candidate wants to take control of the fractious GOP, they need to prove their mettle the old-fashioned way: winning elections.\n\nAnd if the Republicans don't unify behind a new leader, they can expect another loss in 2024. Then in 2026.",
