          "url": "https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/teen-targeted-indian-restaurant-warehouse-25546221",
          "title": "Teen targeted Indian restaurant and warehouse in crime spree",
          "body": "A teenager kicked in the doors of an Indian restaurant then stole cash from a warehouse. Jay Storey from Cwmbran was abusing substances during a crime spree that included stealing cars and burgling homes, a court heard.\n\nLast year Storey was jailed for nine months over a spate of offences from 2020 when he stole two cars and damaged them as well as burgling Halfords in Cwmbran. And he appeared at Newport Magistrates' Court on Thursday to be sentenced for three more crimes from around the same time. The court heard a police error had caused the two-year delay.\n\nProsecutor Emma Davies said a witness woke at 12.10am on August 31, 2020, to hear banging on his street, The Highway in New Inn near Pontypool. He looked out of the window and saw the then-18-year-old Storey kicking in the rear doors of a nearby Indian takeaway. Storey, whose face was covered by a helmet, did not take anything from the restaurant but caused £200 worth of damage to the bolts of the double doors.\n\nRead next: Cardiff's Supajump trampoline park admits criminal offences after four people injured\n\nAround an hour later Storey went to the Ultra Coat powder coating warehouse on Woodfield Road. He kicked through the bottom panel of a door and stole about £200 from a drawer as well as the keys to a van.\n\nMs Davies said Storey had also targeted a home in Trostrey, Cwmbran, at 1.45am the day before. \"Two males approach the driveway and are initially looking at the complainant's car,\" she added. \"Then the defendant goes to approach the home's front door and the side light switches on. The pair do seem to be startled by this and look through the kitchen window. The defendant then tries the door handle with his left hand.\"\n\nStorey, of Brangwyn Avenue, failed to break into the home but admitted attempting burglary. The defendant, now 20, also pleaded guilty to the two Pontypool burglaries. The court heard a Stanley knife was found at one of the crime scenes and a police error meant there was a delay in sending it to forensics. None of Storey's DNA was found on the weapon but the mistake caused a two-year delay in the case.\n\nFrancesca Edwards pointed out her client had admitted the offences in 2020 when interviewed by police. \"Respectfully, forensic evidence doesn't take two years to come back for a matter to be brought to court,\" she said.\n\nThe solicitor added that Storey was at the time experiencing \"a degree of separation\" from his family and \"associating with negative peers\". She told the court: \"These were among a string of burglaries being committed at the time, and this was to do with the group he was associating with. His luck ran out and he ended up going to custody in 2021 for nine months. Had these matters been brought before the court then, he would have received concurrent sentences.\"\n\nConcurrent sentences would have meant Storey serving them at the same time rather than being brought before the court again. The nine-month jail term had come after Storey was convicted of 10 offences including handling a stolen Peugeot 208; stealing and damaging a Mitsubishi Mirage and Honda Civic; stealing a Playstation 4; burgling a Halfords store; and attempting to steal from four homes.\n\nMs Edwards added: \"When he was released from custody he was placed in temporary accommodation which he now shares. That has been successful for him. He has managed to obtain employment at a factory in Abergavenny, which will start immediately after the resolution of this case.\n\n\"He has a positive relationship with his partner and no substance misuse issues, which were the issue in the past. The probation service says he has made huge improvements since his release.\"\n\nPresiding Justice Sian Hodges said it would be \"unjust\" to punish Storey with a community order because \"if this had been brought to court before, it would have been dealt with already and you would have probably had concurrent prison sentences, so we're going to give you a conditional discharge for 12 months\".\n\nA conditional discharge means that if Storey commits another crime in the next 12 months he can be sentenced again for the original offences as well as the new one. Mrs Hodges also ordered him to pay £200 in compensation each to the takeaway and warehouse.\n\nShe told Storey: \"We are encouraged by how you seem to be turning your life around. Hopefully you are older and wiser. We don't wish to see you back before the court.\"\n\nStorey, who receives Personal Independence Payments due to learning difficulties, must also pay £85 in prosecution costs and a £22 victim services surcharge. He will pay the debt at a rate of £10 per fortnight. You can read more of the latest court stories here, and subscribe to our Crime and Punishment court newsletter here.\n\nREAD NEXT:\n\n'Abhorrent' messages on a dead officer's phone paint picture of a 'toxic culture' in Gwent Police\n\n'Our daughter disappeared a year ago. We'll never give up looking for her'\n\nWelsh blogger must pay £50k to Countdown star Rachel Riley after 'abuser' claim\n\n'My daughter was raped, murdered and burned beyond recognition in Qatar'\n\nMan arrested after police seen pointing guns at house near school in Cardiff",
