          "url": "https://www.nj.com/politics/2022/11/3m-car-theft-ring-broken-up-as-nj-continues-to-see-big-surge-in-stolen-vehicles.html",
          "title": "$3M car-theft ring broken up, as N.J. continues to see big surge in stolen vehicles",
          "body": "State Police say they broke up a high-end car theft ring this week with the arrests of five suspects who allegedly stole more than 30 vehicles -- including Land Rovers and BMWs -- worth more than $3 million.\n\nThe charges followed a seven-month investigation that centered in Monmouth County, but involved a wide area spanning 10 counties and New York State.\n\nAccording to investigators, the stolen vehicles would be given fraudulent vehicle identification numbers to be re-titled and then resold online. In some cases, victims were allegedly confronted in their homes by members of the ring in an attempt to steal their late-model vehicles, officials said.\n\nThe arrests come as New Jersey has been confronting a surging car theft problem. There were 14,320 vehicles stolen in the state last year, with thefts up 22% over 2020. Officials expect those numbers to climb even higher this year.\n\n\"We've seen a brazenness, recently. You can hang those keys up on that post in your mudroom, that's a pretty easy spot to get to,\" superintendent of the New Jersey State Police, Col. Patrick Callahan, said last week, as Gov. Phil Murphy on Monday got behind proposed new legislation to address the car theft problem.\n\nThe measures backed by the governor would establish a \"persistent auto theft offender\" statute in New Jersey, that would give state and local prosecutors the option to seek more serious criminal consequences for those who have been repeatedly found guilty of stealing cars. The legislation would also make possession and distribution of certain auto theft tools a crime in the state. A third proposed bill would impose criminal penalties for the failure to comply with certain guidelines in the sale and purchase of catalytic converters in the state.\n\n\"We must do more to reduce the likelihood of car thefts and hold those who do commit these crimes accountable,\" said the governor, noting that too often, stolen cars are being used in shootings and other crimes of violence.\n\n\"We think we've started to bend the curve on the auto theft epidemic,\" he said during a news conference at the State Police headquarters in West Trenton.\n\nMurphy noted that car thefts in September of this year were actually down 14% compared to the prior year and thefts were down 12% in October from the previous year.\n\n\"Progress is in the right direction, but I think we're also here today to acknowledge that we need to do more,\" said the governor.\n\nEarlier this week, Rep. Josh Gottheimer, D-5th Dist., called upon the Department of Homeland Security to do more to stop stolen cars from being illegally exported through the nation's ports. During a Homeland Security Committee hearing in Washington, he told U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security Alejandro Mayorkas that his department needed to take action.\n\n\"Clearly this is a serious issue,\" he said, noting what has become a nationwide rise in car theft, calling the problem not just a local crime issue, but international in scope with the emergence of multi-state and global crime rings.\n\nGottheimer has called for the creation of a National Auto Theft Task Force to coordinate federal, state, and local law enforcement efforts focused on combating interstate and international carjacking and auto theft. He also wants to see a boost in security at Port Newark and other ports to find and intercept more stolen cars before they are loaded into containers and shipped overseas.\n\n\"It feels like every other day we read about yet another carjacking or stolen car literally taken out of someone's driveway as they slept or, brazenly, in broad daylight,\" he said. \"Within minutes, these cars are chopped up for parts or they're brought here where they are immediately put onto ships.\"\n\nIn the arrests announced in Monmouth County this week, State Police said detectives began investigating multiple high-end motor vehicle thefts in Millstone Township and Upper Freehold Township earlier this year, which led to the arrest in July of Geovanni Hernandez, 24, of Newark, who they linked to the thefts of a BMW M8 and three Range Rovers.\n\nFour others were subsequently arrested and charged with conspiracy and theft this week. They included: Carlos Sanchez, 23, who State Police called the leader of the theft ring, along with James Lanier, 24, Solomon Mickens, 23, and Sadiq Griggs, 23, all of Newark. A sixth individual, Destiny Montalvo, 21, also of Newark, was arrested at her home and charged conspiring to dispose of evidence.\n\nAll were being held in the Monmouth County Correctional Institution pending a bail detention hearing.",
